India's New Hope
The latest election in Cambridge, U.S., and India may be the most important positive economic event of 2014.
Indian voters have decisively rejected the Congress party, which has ruled India almost continuously since its independence from Britain in 1947.
They may be happy with this decision.
Sonia Gandhi, the widow of former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, has effectively ruled the country from 1998, while Prime Minister Singh was merely a puppet.
Under her leadership, the Congress Party pursued a populist agenda, increasing transfer payments, which led India's annual economic growth rate to fall below 4% in 2013.
Per capita GDP is still hovering around $4,000, less than half of China's.
The newly elected Prime Minister Narendra Modi had promised to bring rapid growth in employment and income across India, just as he had achieved in his tenure as the Chief Minister of Gujarat.
Under Modi's leadership, Gujarat has become a business-friendly state, economic activities have expanded, and attracted investment from both within and outside India.
One of the key features of the latest election is Modi's Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) secured an absolute majority in the National Assembly, a unprecedented achievement in India.
Therefore, Modi does not need to compromise with other national or regional parties to pursue his legislative schedule.
Two key officials will lend Modi a hand with the economic plan.
New Finance Minister Arun Jaitley has rich political experience, having held ministerial positions in the previous Bharatiya Janata Party government.
Gittler is also known as a strategic thinker sympathetic to business interests.
Raghuram Rajan would continue to serve as the Governor of the Reserve Bank of India. Rajan, a distinguished economist, showed a desire to lower India's high two-digit inflation rate during his tenure as Governor of the Reserve Bank of India, and attempted to reform some of the inherent productivity constraints in India's financial sector.
Measures to stimulate economic growth take time to implement and produce results.
But if you want to know whether the new government is taking action to achieve faster long-term growth, you should examine whether progress has been made in the following ten policy areas.
Education.
Despite India having excellent higher education and technical institutions, only a small portion of people can utilise the opportunities provided by these institutions, as primary and secondary education in India is very backward.
Only 60% of Indian adults have basic literacy.
The teachers themselves have inadequate educational backgrounds, and their working motivation is also insufficient. Many teachers rarely appear at the schools they teach at.
Infrastructure.
India needs better roads and ports to efficiently transport goods across the country and the world.
Recent expansions of private airfields and routes have shown that private endeavors are capable of making a difference in this field.
Fiscal integration.
Large-scale budget deficits absorb national savings, which could have been used to increase business investment. Budget deficits have led to an increase in national debt that will have to be financed by future tax revenues.
Privatization.
The operating efficiency of all manufacturing and other industrial enterprises under the Indian government is low, often resulting in a depletion of national savings.
Selling these enterprises would help accelerate economic growth directly.
Remove subsidies.
Electricity and energy subsidies led to wasteful overconsumption and increased fiscal deficits.
Despite the difficulty in canceling these subsidies politically, they should be replaced with cash transfer payments. Currently, since an impressive fingerprint-based cash transfer new system has been adopted, India's cash transfer payment efficiency is high.
Agricultural reform.
Under the current system, the government purchases, stores, and distributes agricultural products.
The result is that a large number of goods are stockpiled in warehouses, while production incentives have been misguided.
The agricultural market should be privatized.
Property rights and territorial division.
As long as you have been to Mumbai or other major cities in India, you will see that the area division restrictions have led to inefficient use of land in the city and have constrained its development.
Unclear property rights, particularly land rights in rural areas, have hindered the industrialization of rural regions.
Easing restrictions on foreign investment.
Currently, foreign enterprises are unable to become the majority shareholders of banks and insurance companies.
Relaxing these restrictions can strengthen the financial sector and play an important role in economic growth.
Tax Reform.
India's complex system of state and central sales taxes has distorted the domestic trade.
The long debate on replacing these taxes with a national value-added tax and adopting a dual-tax system has gone on for a long time, and it is now time to move to implementation.
Corruption.
High-level corruption scandal has shaken public confidence in the economy and hindered official decision-making.
Corruption, particularly petty bribery, also plagued India, and bribes became a common feature of all business and personal transactions.
The government should severely punish high-level corruption, and limit small-scale corruption through a new cash transfer payment system.
Driven by expectations of a strong economic growth and increasing profits, the Indian stock market has risen by 20% so far this year.
Now, Modi and the Bharatiya Janata Party need to prove to the world that they can deliver on their campaign promises.
